<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Northern Troops Kill 12 Southerners in Attack </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2702120794 Paris AFP in English 1147 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2702120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Aden, Yemen, Feb 27 (AFP) -- Northern Yemeni troops 
attacked a southern brigade with heavy artillery, killing 12 and 
wounding at least 30, a Defence Ministry spokesman said here 
Sunday. 
  The report was denied by a spokesman for President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih's General People's Congress (GPC) in Sanaa, the 
northern capital. 
  The spokesman for the Defence Ministry, which is controlled 
by Salih's southern rival, Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bid, 
said units of the northern first mechanised division attacked a 
base of the southern Fifth Infantry Brigade at Harf Sufyan, 
north of Sanaa, late Saturday. 
  "Twelve members of the (southern) brigade were killed and 
about 30 others wounded," the spokesman said, adding that the 
northern troops prevented the wounded from being evacuated. The 
base was still ringed by northern troops Sunday. 
  A spokesman for al-Bid's Yemen Socialist Party (YSP) 
confirmed that the attack took place. 
  Military mediators from Jordan and Oman drew up a five-point 
plan on Sunday to halt clashes between northern and southern 
army units in which at least 20 people were killed last week. 
  Officials in Sanaa said the mediators called on the opposing 
sides to ban new troop movements, return to their positions 
before the clashes, free prisoners and return the weapons 
seized, dismantle checkpoints and halt the media campaign 
against each other. 
  The GPC, which ruled the former North Yemen, and the YSP, 
which ruled the south, decided to share power when the country 
was united in May 1990, but the armies were not merged. 
  Salih and al-Bid have been locked in a political dispute 
since August, when al-Bid refused to take up his duties as vice 
president in the northern capital Sanaa, demanding major 
economic, political and security reforms. 
  A reconciliation agreement signed in Amman on February 20 
has 
failed so far to end the crisis, and at least 20 soldiers have 
been killed in clashes in the southern Abyan province. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

