<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poland's Walesa, Delegation Arrive for Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sharma Receives Walesa </H4>
<F P=102> BK0303095094 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0303095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] India has expressed willingness to cooperate with 
Poland in a manner beneficial to both the countries. This was 
stated by the president, Dr. Shankar Dayal Sharma, when the 
visiting president of Poland, Mr. Lech Walesa, called on him at 
Rashtrapati Bhavan today. During their 45-minute meeting, Mr. 
Walesa sought India's participation in the changeover to market 
economy in his country. Mr. Walesa said this can be done 
through cooperation in the industrial and technological spheres. 
Besides bilateral matters, the two leaders also exchanged views 
on various regional and international issues, including recent 
developments pertaining to security in Europe. 
  Earlier, the president of Poland, Mr. Lech Walesa, was 
accorded a warm ceremonial reception on his state visit to 
India. The president, Dr. Shankar Dayal Sharma, the prime 
minister, Mr. P.V. Narasimha Rao, and his cabinet colleagues 
were present on the occasion at the Rashtrapati Bhavan this 
morning. Mr. Walesa is accompanied by his wife, Mrs. (Danuta), 
and a high-level delegation, including the foreign minister and 
minister for industry and trade. Talking to newsmen, Mr. Lech 
Walesa said that after the collapse of the Soviet Union, the 
world is looking for new solutions. Mr. Walesa said that his 
country has a lot to learn from the great traditions of India. 
He said there are a number of areas in which bilateral 
cooperation can be enhanced. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

