<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poland's Walesa, Delegation Arrive for Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sharma Hosts Banquet for Walesa </H4>
<F P=102> BK0403032894 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0245 
GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0403032894 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] India and Poland have called for further 
strengthening economic cooperation in the wake of changes in 
both the countries. Speaking at a banquet hosted in honor of the 
visiting Polish president, Mr. Lech Walesa, in New Delhi last 
night, President Dr. Shankar Dayal Sharma, said a sense of 
identity and affinity marks the multi-dimensional growth of ties 
between the two countries. Describing Mr. Walesa's personal 
contribution to Polish revolution as significant, Dr. Sharma 
said the dramatic changes in Poland over the last decade acted 
as an important catalyst in ending the Cold War and 
fundamentally transforming international relations. 
  Reciprocating the sentiments, Mr. Walesa lauded India's 
efforts toward ending the arms race and eliminating the threat 
of nuclear warfare. Turning to the economic front, Mr Walesa 
said there is great scope for increasing trade between the two 
countries and the potential in both the countries should be 
fully exploited. 
  The Polish president also met the vice president, Mr. K.R. 
Narayanan, and stressed the need to project Mahatma Gandhi's 
ideas and values for shaping the new world order. 

</TEXT>

