<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO Letter to Peres Details Talk `Conditions' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0303132694 Tunis Tunisian Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
0600 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0303132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tunis Tunisian Republic Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] After its recent meetings in Tunis following the 
Hebron massacre, the PLO leadership has sent a letter to Israeli 
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres that includes a number of 
conditions before resuming peace talks. Among these conditions 
is the protection of Palestinian citizens. This letter was 
conveyed to the Israeli minister last night by the chairman of 
the EU Council of Ministers, who left Tunisia yesterday, and by 
the Russian deputy foreign minister, who carried a private 
message from President Boris Yeltsin for President Yasir 'Arafat. 
  The chairman of the EU Council of Ministers had also met 
President Yasir 'Arafat. After the meeting, the Israeli foreign 
minister said he was ready to discuss any new conditions with 
the PLO provided they did not contradict with the Declaration of 
Principles. Peres added that some conditions included in the 
organization's letter, like the release of prisoners, had been 
met and that other conditions were unclear. 
  Regarding a likely Security Council resolution concerning 
foreign presence in Gaza and Jericho, Peres said that was 
possible in accordance with what had been stipulated in one of 
the Declaration of Principles' clauses, but that presence would 
not be an alternative to the Palestinian police force, 
increasing the number of which will be discussed by the two 
sides. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

