<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abd-Rabbuh Supports UN Observers' Presence </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0403122994 Paris AFP in English 1219 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0403122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 4 (AFP) -- PLO information chief Yasir 
'Abd-Rabbuh said Friday [25 February] that the presence of 
international observers under UN supervision would greatly help 
to restore Palestinian confidence after the Hebron massacre. 
  'Abd-Rabbuh, speaking after a meeting with French Foreign 
Minister Alain Juppe, said an observer presence "would have a 
very strong symbolic meaning to restore confidence among the 
Palestinians of the occupied territories." 
  Juppe confirmed that France was prepared to send observers 
under United Nations authority, adding that Israel's security 
measures needed to be observed by "international representatives 
mandated by the UN." 
  On Thursday [3 March] British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd 
backed the idea of an international force to protect 
Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and said Britain was 
ready to take part. 
  Juppe said he hoped a UN Security Council resolution on the 
observers would be passed "as soon as possible." The resolution 
has been held up for almost a week because of differences with 
the United States. 
  'Abd-Rabbuh visited Paris as part of a Palestine Liberation 
Organisation effort in world capitals to explain its conditions 
for resuming autonomy negotiations with Israel. 
  The negotiations were broken off after the massacre, in 
which 
52 Palestinians were slaughtered in a mosque by an Israeli 
gunman. 
  Resuming the peace process and putting the autonomy accord 
into effect would be "unthinkable" at a time when "armed 
settlers are walking freely among the Palestinians," 'Abd-Rabbuh 
said. 
  'Abd-Rabbuh will next visit Brussels for a meeting with 
European Commission President Jacques Delors. Nabil Sha'th, PLO 
chairman Yasir Arafat's advisor, met with Hurd in London on 
Thursday before heading for Washington where he was set to meet 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher on Friday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12795 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes043dd_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-043 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

