<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fatah Leader: Israeli Response to Hebron `Cosmetic' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0203154394 Jerusalem AL-QUDS in Arabic 3 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> TA0203154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem AL-QUDS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By 'Ala' al-Mashahrawi] </F>
  [Text] Gaza -- Dr. Zakariya al-Agha, a Fatah leader in the 
Gaza Strip, has described the steps taken by the Israeli 
Government in response to the Ibrahmi Mosque massacre as 
cosmetic steps and as an attempt to deflect the Palestinian and 
Arab peoples' anger. 
  Dr. al-Agha said that those steps are in no way sufficient 
and do not represent serious measures vis-a-vis the size of the 
tragedy that has taken place. He added that the release of a 
few hundred prisoners has no connection with any serious steps, 
especially as the prison term of most of those prisoners was 
about to end. 
  As for the Palestinian leadership's stance toward the 
painful 
massacre and the steps that it has taken, Dr. al-Agha said that 
the Palestinian leadership's response is somewhat acceptable and 
is epitomized by suspending the talks until two basic conditions 
are met. They are: 
  1. Placing the settlements issue as a top priority on the 
agenda and, ultimately, evacuating the settlements and disarming 
the settlers. 
  2. Imposing international protection, with UN supervision, 
in the occupied territories to ensure that the Palestinians live 
in peace and security. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

