<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Committee Rejects Joint Supervision of Shrines </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0403075094 Nicosia FILASTIN AL-THAWRAH in Arabic 20 Feb 94 
p 8 </F>

<F P=103> NC0403075094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia FILASTIN AL-THAWRAH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In a statement distributed on 14 February, the 
Supreme Islamic Committee [SIC] in Jerusalem rejected Israeli 
proposals to discuss the future supervision of the Islamic holy 
shrines in the occupied territories, such as the al-Ibrahimi 
Mosque in Hebron, al-Nabi Yusuf Tomb in Nabulus, al-Nabi Samuil 
Mosque in Jerusalem, and Rachel's Tomb in Bethlehem, on the 
basis that these holy places are sacred to both Muslims and Jews. 
  The statement said: The Islamic mosques should not be a 
place of worship for non-Muslims. The mosques to which the 
proposals refer and that are mentioned in the statement are 
Islamic mosques built by Muslims. 
  The statement added: The current practices in the mosques 
are based on the force of the occupation. From the beginning, 
the SIC has objected to these practices, stressing its adherence 
to the Muslim holy shrines and mosques. 

</TEXT>

