<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Briefs Russian Envoy on PLO Position </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0603205294 Sanaa Voice of Palestine in Arabic 1800 GMT 6 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0603205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Voice of Palestine </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brother Abu-'Ammar [Yasir 'Arafat], president of 
the state of Palestine and head of the PLO Executive Committee, 
has received special Russian envoy Igor Ivanov, who has been 
visiting Israel. The Palestinian News Agency, WAFA, indicated 
that Ivanov acquainted brother Abu-'Ammar with the outcome of 
his talks with the Israeli prime minister and foreign minister. 
  Brother Abu-'Ammar laid out for the Russian envoy the PLO's 
basic demand that protection for the Palestinians in the 
occupied territories be ensured before the talks can be resumed. 
Brother Abu-'Ammar reiterated the PLO's position that the 
United Nations must secure protection for the Palestinians and 
disarm Jewish settlers. The brother president, WAFA adds, told 
the Russian envoy he was disturbed that the UN Security Council 
found it hard to pass a resolution that would make it possible 
for the peace talks to resume and for secure protection for the 
Palestinians throughout the occupied territories to be ensured. 
The meeting took place in a cordial atmosphere and demonstrated 
that the Palestinian and Russian viewpoints were identical. 
  According to a Palestinian source, brother Abu-'Ammar 
earlier 
received the U.S. ambassador in Tunis, John McCarthy, to discuss 
continuing consultations about a UN Security Council resolution 
on the Ibrahimi Mosque massacre. Russia is widely thought to be 
in favor of a resolution providing for international protection 
for the Palestinians in the occupied territories, while the 
United States and Israel are opposed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

