<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO Officials Hold Consultations on Negotiations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0703095094 Amman AL-DUSTUR in Arabic 7 Mar 94 pp 32, 24 </F>
<F P=103> JN0703095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-DUSTUR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Amman -- AL-DUSTUR has learned that several PLO 
Executive Committee members in Amman continue to hold meetings 
and consultations to formulate a unified stand on the resumption 
of Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations. 
  Some of those holding such contacts are Yasir 'Amr, Sulayman 
al-Najjab, Muhammad Zuhdi al-Nashashibi, Taysir Khalid, and 
'Abd-al-Rahim Malluh. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12814 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes044dd_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-044 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th Reiterates Call for UN Force in Territories </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0603171494 Stockholm Radio Sweden in Swedish 1545 GMT 6 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0603171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm Radio Sweden </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Both the PLO leadership and the Israeli Government 
want to restart the peace process, but the question is to what 
extent Israel thinks it can meet the PLO's demands. We will 
first go over to Oslo, which is being visited by PLO negotiators: 
  [Correspondent Johan Fredriksson] The PLO's main condition 
for resuming the peace talks is that armed UN supervisors should 
be stationed in the occupied territories. It does not have to 
be a big force, the PLO's chief negotiator Nabil Sha'th said 
when he visited Oslo today. 
  [Begin Sha'th recording, in English] We are not calling for 
a 
major army of separation. We need the presence--the strong, 
effective presence--of people who know about security, and that 
is, I think, why we needed armed observers. [end recording] 
  [Fredriksson] In addition to this, however, the Israeli 
Government must, on the one hand, put an end to the violence 
that its own army uses in Gaza and on the West Bank. On the 
other hand, it must also disarm the militant settlers in the 
regions, Sha'th says. 
  [Begin Sha'th recording, in English] Half the element is to 
have an international presence; the other half is to have an 
Israeli restriction of the settler violence. [end recording] 
  [Fredriksson] This is Johan Fredriksson in Oslo. 

</TEXT>

