<H3> <TI>   MENA Previews Upcoming Mubarak, Arafat Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Musa Meets 'Arafat Upon Arrival </H4>
<F P=102> NC0603164494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1638 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0603164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 6 Mar (MENA)--Palestinian President Yasir 
'Arafat arrived in Cairo this evening. He is due to hold talks 
with President Muhammad Husni Mubarak and make a complete 
assessment of the peace process and the latest developments 
following the Ibrahimi Mosque massacre. 
  Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa received 'Arafat upon his 
arrival. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12827 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes044_c_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-044 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   MENA Previews Upcoming Mubarak, Arafat Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Foriegn Minister Comments </H4>
<F P=102> NC0603205894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2020 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0603205894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 6 Mar (MENA)--Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa has 
stated that President Husni Mubarak and Palestinian President 
Yasir 'Arafat discussed the situation in the occupied Arab 
territories and the impact of the al-Ibrahimi Mosque's incident 
on the peace process. 
  In a statement following the conclusion of the 
Mubarak-'Arafat talks this evening, Musa said the two presidents 
also discussed the issues of settlements and Palestinian 
security in the occupied territories. 
  Musa said the security issue concerns not only the Israelis 
but both the Arabs and Israelis. Therefore, from now on we 
cannot speak about Israeli security without talking about 
Palestinian security on an equal footing. 
  Musa explained that the demonstrations that were staged in 
Jerusalem today to protest the al-Ibrahimi Mosque incident 
supported peace. They definitely encourage and give the 
impression that forces desiring peace from the Palestinian and 
Israeli sides can play a role in encouraging an agreement. 
  Musa said: We have never said that all Israelis are 
settlers. But we have spoken about these extremist and 
aggressive gunmen who commit crimes against the Palestinians in 
the occupied territories. This is why we have spoken about 
disarming the outlaw elements in some organizations. 
  Asked if the Palestinians insist that the UN Security 
Council 
issue a resolution providing protection for the Palestinian 
people, Musa said the Security Council resolution should refer 
to the security and protection of the Palestinians. Moreover, 
the Israeli Government is dutybound to take measures to protect 
the Palestinians from the settlers' attacks and the terrorist 
organizations inside the settlements. 
  On whether Israel is prepared to accept the presence of 
international observers in the occupied territories, Musa said 
there is a basis for this in the Declaration of Principles, in 
which Israel accepted a foreign presence between them and the 
Palestinians. This indicates that this idea is not ruled out. 
However, what is being discussed now at the Security Council is 
the protection of the Palestinians in the rest of the occupied 
territories, that is in the West Bank as well. 
  Musa added that we are speaking about a framework during the 
next two weeks envisaging the disarming of the settlements, 
protecting the Palestinians, and disbanding the terrorist 
organizations. There must be decisive Israeli measures because, 
under international law, Israel is responsible for the 
territories under its military occupation. 
  Asked about the statements by U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher following his meeting with Dr. Nabil Sha'th, 
political adviser to Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat, and 
whether these statements indicate a U.S. conviction for the need 
to provide protection for the Palestinians, Musa expressed his 
appreciation of the stands of the United States and Europe and 
of their awareness of these considerations. He stressed that 
there is a worldwide understanding of this issue. 
  On the date of the resumption of the Israeli-Palestinian 
talks, Musa said setting a date is not being discussed now 
although the negotiating track still exists. 
  Asked if the al-Ibrahimi Mosque incident will make it 
difficult to convince the Arab people to continue the peace 
process, Musa said that the crime that was committed in the 
al-Ibrahimi Mosque provoked Arab people everywhere, including 
the Egyptian people and Government. We are all together in this 
and are angry over what happened. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-12828 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes044_c_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-044 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   MENA Previews Upcoming Mubarak, Arafat Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   'Arafat Adviser Arrives, Comments </H4>
<F P=102> NC0603214294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2125 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0603214294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 6 Mar (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political 
adviser to Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat and head of the 
Palestinian delegation to the peace talks, arrived in Cairo 
tonight after a tour of the United States, Britain, and Norway. 
  Upon his arrival, Sha'th said he will brief President 
'Arafat 
on the outcome of his tour, which focused on how to respond to 
the Palestinian people's need for security following the 
criminal al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre in Hebron. He expressed 
the belief that the most important outcome of his tour was the 
agreement of the U.S., British, and Norwegian Governments that 
providing security for the Palestinians is a top priority before 
the peace process can be resumed. The three governments also 
believe that the Palestinian demand is just and must be met. 
  Dr. Sha'th said that British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd 
expressed his country's full consent to the presence of UN 
forces in the occupied territories and British participation in 
them. The Norwegian foreign minister explained that his country 
has issued orders to the Norwegian Armed Forces and Norwegian 
planes are ready to take off immediately once a resolution is 
issued in this respect. 
  Dr. Sha'th said the Americans have declared their agreement 
in principle but want time to study the measures and discuss the 
subject with Israel. 
  Dr. Sha'th explained that in principle the three parties 
agree on the need to restrain the terrorist settlers and prevent 
the Israelis from carrying weapons in Palestinian towns and 
villages. They also agree on other measures to reduce the 
violence by the Israeli army, which after the massacre killed 
people in numbers nearly equal to those in the massacre. 
  Dr. Sha'th said that the three parties affirmed the need to 
return to the talks quickly so that the Israeli withdrawal can 
take place before 13 April. 
  Dr. Sha'th stressed that Egypt will remain a full partner in 
the talks, whether they are held in Cairo or Washington. He 
noted that it is especially significant that he started his tour 
in Egypt and returned at the end. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

