<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   MENA Previews Upcoming Mubarak, Arafat Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Musa, 'Arafat Hold News Conference </H4>
<F P=102> NC0703090494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0715 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0703090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 7 Mar (MENA)--Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa and 
Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat held a press conference at 
the conclusion of their two-hour talks last evening. 
  'Arafat opened the conference by saying: I extend my 
heartfelt thanks to President Husni Mubarak, who is standing 
firmly and strongly with the Palestinian people, their cause, 
and their sanctities. 
  'Arafat expressed his appreciation of the firm stance Egypt 
has taken with the Palestinian people vis-a-vis the heinous 
massacre in the al-Ibrahimi Mosque. I have asked President 
Mubarak to make efforts with all the parties concerned in the UN 
Security Council to follow up on this matter, he said, adding: 
I discussed this matter with Minister 'Amr Musa. 
  On resuming the peace negotiations, 'Arafat said: We cannot 
talk about negotiations until we see what the situation will be 
like at the Security Council and until we see the resolution it 
will adopt. We insist on full condemnation of this heinous 
crime, international protection for our people, and disarming 
settlement inhabitants, he stressed. 
  'Arafat emphasized the need for protecting the Palestinian 
people, emphasizing that withdrawing settlers from Hebron is 
essential because these settlements are dangerous. He added 
that the Israeli Government must take effective and swift 
measures to control the settlers, because this is its 
responsibility. 
  Answering a question on the outcome of the talks his 
adviser, 
Dr. Nabil Sha'th, held in the United States, 'Arafat said: We 
hope the United States will take a clear-cut stance to urge the 
Security Council to issue a resolution--this is very important 
for the occupied territories, particularly Jerusalem--to disarm 
settlers and provide international protection for the 
Palestinians. 
  'Arafat added that the most important thing is to determine 
the party that will take charge of protecting Palestinians, 
because we have an army [as received] to protect the 
Palestinians from these settlers. 
  'Arafat affirmed that units of the Israeli Army were 
involved 
in the massacre in the al-Ibrahimi Mosque. 
  Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa remarked that the situation is 
too 
serious to be addressed in a sentimental manner. The matter 
needs specific measures, he emphasized. 
  The foreign minister underlined the need for the UN Security 
Council to issue a resolution and enforce certain measures to 
protect the Palestinians against aggression by the Israeli 
settlers. 
  Speaking about the minimum Palestinian demands, Musa said 
that President 'Arafat has already stated this clearly: a UN 
Security Council resolution and certain measures to guarantee 
protection for the Palestinians and their safety. The 
settlements cannot be left the way they are now because this 
will lead to a repetition of the al-Ibrahimi Mosque incident, 
Musa said, hoping the Security Council will adopt a resolution 
as soon as possible. 
  The UN Security Council resolution must involve the minimum 
Palestinian demands that are supported by the Arab states and 
the international community, he stressed. We are very upset at 
the delay in issuing a resolution because the Hebron incident 
cannot pass without taking specific measures to avert a 
recurrence and in the meantime protect the Palestinians in 
accordance with the international resolutions that should be 
respected, he emphasized. 
  The foreign minister reiterated that all are acting to issue 
a resolution and enforce certain measures to protect the 
Palestinians. We have expressed our regrets and our denunciation 
of what happened in Hebron, he said, adding that the issue of 
Palestinian protection and settlers must be taken into 
consideration. 
  Musa pointed out that as an occupying force, Israel is fully 
responsible for protecting the Palestinians according to the 4th 
Geneva agreement. He said that the West Bank and Gaza are under 
Israeli occupation, according to UN Security Council Resolution 
242. 

</TEXT>

