<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daily Urges `Radical Solution' to Settlements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0603080194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0705 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0603080194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 6 Mar (MENA)--The newspaper AL-AHRAM has 
emphasized that the problems resulting from the widening scope 
of extremist actions in the region requires that their impact on 
the Middle East peace process be neutralized. This problem 
requires a radical solution because the developments over the 
past two years have shown that such a solution is in the best 
interests of all parties. In an editorial today, the paper says 
that it is insufficient to disarm the extremists in settlements 
or even to impose international protection of the Palestinians 
as a temporary measure until the issue of settlements has been 
resolved, noting that a basic solution lies in deporting the 
settlers and extremists from the occupied land. 
  AL-AHRAM states that the Israeli views of keeping the 
settlements in the occupied territories have become 
old-fashioned given the new realities of Jewish extremism. The 
paper says that certain facts about Jewish extremism that 
emerged after the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre showed that there 
are training camps and command posts that extend to the United 
States. In addition, these realities demonstrated the American 
Jews' support for the Jewish extremists in Israel and inside the 
occupied territories, a fact that has made the U.S. 
Administration express its concern. 

</TEXT>

