<F P=101> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Velayati, PRC Official Interviewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0403155094 Tehran IRIB Television Second Program Network 
in English 1400 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0403155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRIB Television Second Program Network 
in English 1400 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] China's deputy prime minister and foreign minister, 
Mr. Qian Qichen, arrived in Tehran on Friday morning and was 
welcomed at Mehrabad International Airport by Foreign Affairs 
Minister Velayati. Mr. Qian and his delegation are expected to 
stay in Iran for two days. A top-ranking political- economic 
delegation accompanies Mr. Qian Qichen in his visit to Iran. 
  Shortly after arriving, China's foreign minister took part 
in 
a press conference, which was also attended by Iran's foreign 
minister. The visiting Chinese official expressed his happiness 
at being in Iran and referred to Sino-Iranian ties as sincere 
and fruitful. Pointing to the Islamic Republic of Iran as a 
country bridging Asia and Europe, Mr. Qian added: The Republic 
of China believes establishing healthy relations with Iran 
should bear positive effects not only in the region, but also in 
the world arena. 
  China's deputy prime minister then referred to the two 
states' economic ties and said: 
  [Begin Qian recording in Chinese, with superimposed English 
translation] The level of trade exchanges between China and Iran 
are satisfactory; declaring that both nations are willing to 
expand reciprocal cooperation in various economic fields. [end 
recording] 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified correspondent] Mr. Foreign 
Minister, how do you view Mr. Qian's visit to Iran and what 
issues are likely to be discussed between you and your Chinese 
counterpart? 
  [Velayati] In the Name of God, the Merciful, the 
Compassionate. Mr. Qian Qichen is my old friend and has been the 
Foreign Minister of China since a long time ago. During last few 
years he paid one official visit to our country, and this is the 
second official visit which he has paid to our country on the 
basis of my invitation; and we are going to talk about the 
bilateral and also international issues. You know that after 
the Islamic revolution we have promoted our relations with China 
in different fields. And also as far as the international 
affairs are concerned, we have had very close cooperation during 
the last years, especially in the United Nations and other 
international organizations. 
  Recently in Jakarta, China was accepted as an observer in 
the 
Nonaligned Movement. So, not only at the United Nations, but 
also in the Nonaligned Movement we cooperate together. Iran and 
China as two important Asian countries can play a very important 
role for peace and tranquillity in this part of the world. 
  [Correspondent] Thank you. [end recording] 
  Regional issues, including the Palestinian question, are 
among the most crucial topics which the two sides said they will 
take into serious consideration. The Chinese foreign minister 
stated his country strongly condemns the massacre of Muslim 
Palestinians by the Zionist soldiers in the town of Hebron in 
the occupied land. 
  As for the uproar by the West on human rights in China, Mr. 
Qian Qichen said: China does not allow any foreign country to 
interfere in its internal affairs, adding that his country acts 
on the basis of China's judicial laws and system, not on the 
basis of the criteria favored by the West. 
  At the end of the press conference, the two foreign 
ministers 
emphasized joint participation in the international meetings and 
gatherings, and hoped that Iran and China would adopt further 
common policies towards regional and global affairs. 
  Iran and China have long enjoyed most friendly mutual 
relations. Mr. Qian's visit, however, is viewed as an affair to 
further activate the two countries' bilateral cooperation 
concerning regional and international issues. 

</TEXT>

