<H3> <TI>   Peres on Peace Process, Meeting 'Arafat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0603193494 London MBC Television in Arabic 1800 GMT 6 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0603193494 </F>
<F P=104>  London MBC Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks in English with </F>
superimposed translation into Arabic] 
  [Text] In an exclusive interview with MBC, Israeli Foreign 
Minister Shim'on Peres called for the resumption of peace talks 
between Israel and the PLO, saying that such a move would 
benefit both sides. 
  Responding to a question on the difficulties that the Hebron 
massacre has created for the peace talks and the fact that the 
massacre brought to the fore once again the issue of 
settlements, settlers, and their restraining effect on the peace 
process, Peres said: 
  [Begin recording] [Peres] "I admit that what happened 
created 
many pressures and problems for us. We have to find the 
suitable solutions. In my opinion, the most important 
development that should happen now is the implementation of the 
agreement, not its revision. I believe that the Palestinians 
and Arabs will feel a dramatic change once they are in control 
of their lives in Gaza and Jericho. Soon afterward, it will be 
possible to begin negotiating other matters. But if we scrap 
the agreement and start on a new one, we will remain suspended 
in midair for a long time and people will lose patience and 
eventually confidence in the possibility of achieving peace." 
  [Correspondent Mahir Shalabi] There is talk of a possible 
meeting between you and Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat 
tomorrow in Cairo. 
  [Peres] "No agreement has been made about this meeting so 
far." 
  [Shalabi] If this meeting takes place, one of the issues 
that 
will be put before you is the deployment of international forces 
in the occupied territories. 
  [Peres] "If the meeting takes place and this subject is 
brought up, I will probably have an answer." [end recording] 

</TEXT>

