<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meretz Faction Opposes Tzomet Inclusion in Government </TI></H3>
<H4>   Inclusion Rejected at `Present Time' </H4>
<F P=102> TA0303173194 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 1400 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0303173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by party affairs correspondent Sefi Hendler] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] It looks as though Prime 
Minister Rabin is seriously pursuing the move to expand the 
coalition. Today, he held a phone conversation with Minister 
Shulamit Aloni and explained to her that not all the reports 
regarding this issue are accurate. Rabin told Meretz leader 
Aloni he wants to meet Meretz ministers tomorrow in order to 
explain the situation to them. 
  Meanwhile the Meretz Knesset faction convened in Tel Aviv 
today and decided to reject Tzomet's inclusion in the coalition 
at the present time. Environment Minister Yosi Sarid explains 
the decisions of his party: 
  [Begin Sarid recording] Meretz believes that the inclusion 
of Tzomet in the government at the present time is unwarranted 
and should be rejected. In the wake of the Hebron massacre and 
its grave repercussions Tzomet's inclusion would send out a 
negative message to our Palestinian interlocutors, Israeli Arabs 
and their public and Knesset representatives, and would have an 
adverse effect on the peace process' chances of quickly 
proceeding toward a positive conclusion. [end recording] 
  It is worthwhile to note that Minister Sarid put the 
emphasis 
on the present time. Meretz believes that at the present time 
Tzomet's inclusion would harm the peace process, but in a few 
months -- after the first stage of the Oslo agreement is 
implemented -- conditions could change. 
  Meretz's statement also mentioned SHAS [Torah Observing 
Sephardim], calling on it to return to the coalition. Meretz is 
perhaps signalling to Rabin that they are willing to compromise 
on SHAS' return to the coalition. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

