<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meretz Faction Opposes Tzomet Inclusion in Government </TI></H3>
<H4>   Threatens To Leave Coalition </H4>
<F P=102> TA0503202394 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 2000 GMT 5 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0503202394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A coalition crisis is possible. The Meretz Knesset 
faction threatens to walk out of the coalition the moment Labor 
starts negotiating with Tzomet on joining the government. This 
was decided tonight in a meeting attended by Meretz ministers 
and its caucus. Meretz notes that the coalition agreement gives 
it veto powers over other parties joining the coalition, and it 
is certain that Prime Minister Rabin will abide by the 
agreement. Our correspondent Shmu'el Tal reports that Meretz 
says that coopting Tzomet into the coalition will constitute a 
negative message to the PLO leadership, Israel's Arab community, 
and the entire peace process. 
  Minister Shulamit Aloni informed Prime Minister Rabin of the 
Meretz decision. She said his response was indignation and that 
he said he would continue contacts with Tzomet. Minister Aloni 
said the prime minister thinks Meretz has to do his bidding and 
that he demands more from it than from his own party. She said 
they are two separate parties and the Meretz position also has 
to be taken into account. 
  Tzomet leader Refa'el Eytan told our correspondent that 
following the Meretz decision his information permits 
negotiations into Tzomet joining the government. 
  Labor Secretary General Nisim Zvili said the Meretz decision 
is strange. It is unclear why they rule out Tzomet, which is 
ready to join on the basis of the government's basic guidelines, 
he said. 

</TEXT>

