<H3> <TI>   Salih Accuses `Southern Rivals' of Conspiracy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0603205694 Amman Jordan Television Network in English 2000 
GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0603205694 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News at Ten" program] </F>
  [Text] Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih accused his 
southern rivals of conspiring to divide the country and vowed to 
prevent a split at any prince. 
  In a televised speech last night, President Salih said unity 
was a fact of life and that any thinking of secession is out of 
the question. He said it will not happen no matter what the 
price will be. 
  President Salih indirectly accused Vice President 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid's Yemen Socialist Party of heightening military tensions. 
He said he warned those who insist on this course that they 
will pay the price. 
  He said a joint Yemeni-Jordanian and Omani military 
committee, which also includes the U.S. and French military 
attaches in Sanaa, was working to end the military tension and 
for the return of forces to their original bases. 

</TEXT>

