<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Views Change in UK, French Position on Embargo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0603095094 Baghdad INA in Arabic 0720 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN0603095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Baghdad, 6 Mar (INA)--The AL-JUMHURIYAH newspaper 
says the United States has become virtually isolated in its 
calls for the continued enforcement of sanctions against Iraq, 
particularly since it has seen with its own eyes the 
disintegration of its international coalition. 
  In an article published today, the paper adds: Despite the 
fact that the U.S. position on the embargo has remained 
unchanged, as attested to by the recent report Clinton submitted 
to the U.S. Congress, there has been a change in the French and 
British positions on the embargo. 
  AL-JUMHURIYAH adds: The French position is showing signs of 
change, as manifested in the Iraqi-French political and oil 
talks and the statements made by the French foreign minister, in 
which he said that there is a strong likelihood of Iraq resuming 
its oil exports shortly. 
  The paper goes on to say: Despite the fact that the British 
position on the embargo is still close to the U.S. position, 
there has been a noticeable watering down of the intransigent 
anti-Iraq rhetoric used by British officials. As for Russia and 
the PRC, they are sympathetic to the efforts to lift the embargo 
imposed on Iraq. 
  AL-JUMHURIYAH says: These indications, coupled with Iraq's 
cooperation and its implementation of the provisions enshrined 
in the relevant UN Security Council resolutions, underscore the 
need to lift the embargo, because there are no justifications 
for maintaining it. 
  The paper concludes by saying: The continuation of the 
embargo means that Washington is implementing the most dangerous 
chapter of its grand anti-Iraq conspiracy, and that it is 
working to stifle Iraq; and this is something the Iraqi people 
oppose and will never accept. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

