<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Highest Level' Contacts Under Way To Resume Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0703121994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1150 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0703121994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 7 Mar (MENA)--MENA has learned that 
diplomatic contacts are being held on the "highest level" in 
Cairo to work out a Palestinian-Israeli formula to overcome the 
obstacles hindering a UN Security Council resolution condemning 
the al-Ibrahimi Mosque massacre, providing international 
protection for the Palestinian people in the occupied 
territories, and taking into account the resumption of 
negotiations in accordance with a Palestinian-Israeli bilateral 
agreement. 
  Diplomatic sources have told MENA that the current brief 
visit to Cairo by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin's 
political adviser Jacques Neriya, comes within these accelerated 
contacts. 'Arafat categorically rejected a meeting in Cairo 
with Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres at Peres' request. 
  MENA has learned that the visiting Israeli envoy is carrying 
a proposal to hold an urgent meeting in Cairo or Washington 
between 'Arafat and Rabin to reach a formula for an agreement to 
resume the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations. 
  The agency has also learned that the Israeli side is willing 
to implement the Gaza-Jericho Agreement within three weeks from 
the conclusion of negotiations in this connection. 
  The Egyptians and Palestinians are making contacts with the 
United States in its capacity as a sponsor of the peace process 
to guarantee the safety of the Palestinian people and work out a 
new basis for negotiations in the stage to come. 
  Official Palestinian sources have told MENA that no meeting 
between 'Arafat and Peres is acceptable right now and under the 
current circumstances, especially as the Palestinian people are 
worried and lack confidence in the Israeli Government's promises. 
  Diplomatic sources told MENA that in light of the 
Palestinians' refusal to meet with Peres, Greek Foreign Minister 
Karolos Papoulias, current chairman of the EU's Ministerial 
Council, has requested an urgent meeting with Palestinian 
President Yasir 'Arafat. In that meeting, held at Cairo 
Airport, Papoulias handed 'Arafat Israeli proposals aiming to 
overcome the obstacles facing the resumption of the 
Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations. 
  The Palestinian side, MENA learned, rejected the Israeli 
proposals, which aim to reach a bilateral deal sidestepping the 
UN Security Council. The Israeli proposals are in line with the 
policy approved by the Israeli cabinet in its 27 February 
session. 
  The main features of this policy are: 
  - Emptying the Hebron area of settlers. 
  - Forming a committee of inquiry into the al-Ibrahimi 
Mosque massacre. 
  - Taking tougher measures against "some" extremist Israeli 
settlers in the West Bank, such as: 
  a. The institution of administrative detention. 
  b. The imposition of military restrictions and control on 
the movement of some extremists into the West Bank, particularly 
Hebron. 
  c. The cancellation of the gun licenses of some extremist 
Israeli settlers and their disarmament. 
  d. The Israeli Government's legal adviser is to examine 
the possibility of outlawing the Kakh and Kahane groups. 
  e. The release of 1,000 Palestinian detainees. Eight 
hundred were released last week. 
  The Israeli Government also decided to pay compensation for 
the families of the victims of the Hebron massacre. 
  According to the same diplomatic sources, the massacre at 
the 
al-Ibrahimi Mosque in Hebron has created a new reality 
necessitating a new form of dealing and communication between 
the Palestinians and the Israelis. The Israelis, for their 
part, are still trying to prevent the condemnation of the 
massacre by the UN Security Council. 
  According to these sources, Rabin maintains that he cannot 
control the domestic situation in Israel in view of the 
fragility of the current coalition. It is worth noting that a 
wave of anger swept through Israel following the massacre. 
  The Palestinians, meanwhile, insist on international 
protection of Palestinians living in the occupied territories. 
Such protection, the Palestinians say, can be provided through 
the deployment of international observes working either under a 
mandate from the UN Security Council or a Palestinian-Israeli 
agreement. Such agreement would specify the number and 
nationalities of the observers, along the line of the existing 
agreement between Egypt and Israel. 
  The Palestinians also insist that all Palestinian detainees 
in Israel be promptly released. They note that the Palestinian 
need for security guarantees matches that of the settlers. 
  It is worth noting that 9,400 Palestinians are in Israeli 
jails and detention camps, in accordance with the latest Red 
Cross count. 
  The Palestinians also seek improved living conditions for 
the 
Palestinians living in the occupied territories until the 
implementation of the self-rule agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

