<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinian Official on Disputes in Economic Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0703195994 London MBC Television in Arabic 1800 GMT 7 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0703195994 </F>
<F P=104>  London MBC Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Economic Cast"] </F>
  [Text] Ahmad Quray', alias Abu-'Ala', chairman of the 
Palestinian Reconstruction and Development Council has told MBC 
Television that Palestinian and Israeli delegations, who have so 
far held five rounds of economic negotiations, are having 
differences over the issue of trade and customs duties. 
  [Begin Quray' recording] We have made some progress on 
banking and financial issues but we are having a real dispute 
over trade and customs duties. I wish to point out that, first 
of all, a new reality has come into being and we must handle 
issues on the basis of this. The Palestinian territory cannot 
remain in the same condition during the transitional period as 
it was during the occupation phase. A new reality exists that 
should apply to all spheres of activity, be they political, 
economic, or social. This is the new reality. Another issue is 
the following: According to the Declaration of Principles there 
will be economic cooperation with Israel but the Palestinians 
will continue to have strategic economic relations with their 
larger Arab homeland. Israel must understand the Palestinian 
trade relationship with the Arab homeland. The Palestinians 
must make their own decisions on this matter. A third area of 
dispute is connected with our determination to decide the level 
of customs duties and taxes to be imposed on economic 
development projects. We must also be the only authority to 
determine how much tax is paid on certain basic commodities. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

