<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Acknowledges Bombing SPLA Positions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0503114994 Dakar PANA in English 1105 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0503114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Dakar PANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kampala, 5 Mar (PANA) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister 
Husayn Sulayman Abu-Salih, said in Kampala on Saturday [5 March] 
that bombing raids being carried out by the Sudanese Airforce on 
position held by the rebel Sudanese Peoples Liberation Army 
(SPLA), is aimed at forcing them to the negotiating table. 
"Much as the Sudan favours a cease-fire and a complete 
cessation of hostilities, previous experiences have shown that 
treating the issue of the cease-fire separately is a futile 
exercise", the foreign minister told a press conference in 
Kampala. 
  Abu-Salih who arrived in Uganda from Kenya on Friday, with a 
message from President 'Umar al-Bashir to Preesident Yoweri 
Museveni said, Khartoum believes that fighting is not a solution 
to war. "We want a just and genuine peace in the Sudan", he 
said. He claimed that much of the fighting in the southern 
Sudan is betwen the rebel factions themselves and tribes hostile 
to the rebels. 
  The foreign minister who returns back to Kenya Saturday said 
Sudan fully supports peace initiatives by the four heads of 
state in the Inter-Governmental Authority on Desertification and 
Development (IGADD), the objectives of which is to reach a 
negotiated peaceful settlement of the civil war in the southern 
Sudan. 
  "These countries sharing the same borders with the Sudan, 
being fully knowladgable of the root causes of the problem, are 
better placed to help bring about the desired peaceful 
settlement", he said. He added however, that proper 
negotiations should be consucted by his government and the 
rebels to reach a peaceful settlement. 
  The Khartoum [as received] in 1992 launched the latest 
massive military operation against the southern rebels led by 
the SPLA which accused the central governmment of trying to 
Islamise the entire country. 

</TEXT>

