<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military `Failed' To Secure Troop Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0703144494 Baghdad INA in Arabic 1345 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN0703144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, 7 Mar (INA)--The Yemeni joint military 
committee has failed to persuade the commanders of some Yemeni 
brigades to return to their old positions outside al-Bayda' 
Governorate in accordance with the authorization the committee 
obtained from the Yemeni president and Vice President 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid to end the military tensions between northern and 
southern Yemeni troops. 
  The newspaper AL-MUSTAQBAL, mouthpiece of the Yemeni 
Socialist Party, today reported that the committee, which also 
includes Jordanian and Omani military officers, had to leave 
al-Bayda' Governorate without ending the tension there. 
  The troops, which the committee failed to return to their 
original positions, were brought into al-Bayda' Governorate from 
various Yemeni towns following the military friction that has 
been going on since 20 February between southern units loyal to 
the Yemeni Socialist Party and northern units. They include the 
56th Armored Brigade and two other brigades, as well as units 
from the Central Security Forces and a Republican Guard 
battalion. 
  The paper notes that the military committee's failure in 
al-Bayda' Governorate heralds other failures in other areas. 

</TEXT>

